To solve this, we first calculate the current enrollment as a percentage of the capacity.
\begin{align*} \frac{980 \text{ students}}{1100 \text{ total students}} \amp= \frac{x}{100} \\ 980\cdot 100 \amp= 1100x \\ \frac{980\cdot 100}{1100} \amp= x \\ 89.1\amp\approx x \end{align*}
This means the current enrollment is 89.1 percent of capacity. Next, we calculate the percentage for every percent increase in enrollment.
\begin{align*} \frac{105\text{ students}}{1100 \text{ students}} \amp= \frac{x}{100} \\ 105\cdot 100 \amp= 1100x \\ \frac{105\cdot 100}{1100} \amp= x \\ 9.55 \amp\approx x \end{align*}
This means that enrollment increases approximately 9.55 percent every year. We need to calculate when 980 students raised by 9.55 percent becomes 1100, the capacity of the school.
$$1100=x+9.55x$$
The solution is $n=\text{ } \underline6 \text{.}$</think> <answer> Interpret the given information in terms of the percentage, then solve the inequality.
\begin{align*} \frac{980}{1100} \amp\lt100\text{$\%$}\\ 980 \cdot \left(\frac{105}{1100}\right)^n \amp\lt 1100\text{$\%$}\\ \log \left(0.93\cdot 105\right)^n \amp\lt \log(1.1)\\ \log(0.93)+n \log105 \amp\lt \log 1.1\\ n \log 105 \amp\lt \log 1.1-\log(0.93)\\ n \amp\gt \frac{\log 1.1-\log(0.93)}{\log 105}\\ \amp\approx 5.66 \end{align*}
This means there will be a jump in enrollment every year. We need to find the smallest integer that is greater than 5.66, which is $ \boxed{6}$. </answer>

solution:
Let
\[f(x) = \frac{1}{x - 1} + \frac{2}{x - 2} + \frac{3}{x - 3} + \dots + \frac{100}{x - 100}.\]Consider the graph of $y = f(x).$

[asy]
unitsize(1 cm);

real func(real x) {
  return((1/(x - 1) + 2/(x - 2) + 3/(x - 3) + 4/(x - 4) + 5/(x - 5) + 6/(x - 6))/15);
}

draw((-2,0)--(8,0));
draw((0,-2)--(0,2));
draw((1,-2)--(1,2),dashed);
draw((2,-2)--(2,2),dashed);
draw((3,-2)--(3,2),dashed);
draw((5,-2)--(5,2),dashed);
draw((6,-2)--(6,2),dashed);
draw((-2,-2/4)--(8,8/4));
draw(graph(func,-2,0.99),red);
draw(graph(func,1.01,1.99),red);
draw(graph(func,2.01,2.99),red);
draw(graph(func,5.01,5.99),red);
draw(graph(func,6.01,8),red);

limits((-2,-2),(8,2),Crop);

label("$1$", (1,0), SW);
label("$2$", (2,0), SW);
label("$3$", (3,0), SE);
label("$99$", (5,0), SW);
label("$100$", (6,0), SE);
label("$y = x$", (8,2), E);
label("$y = f(x)$", (8,func(8)), E, red);
[/asy]

The graph of $y = f(x)$ has vertical asymptotes at $x = 1,$ $x = 2,$ $\dots,$ $x = 100.$  In particular, $f(x)$ approaches $-\infty$ as $x$ approaches $n$ from the left, and $f(x)$ approaches $\infty$ as $x$ approaches $n$ from the right, for $1 \le n \le 100.$  Furthermore, $y = 0$ is a vertical asymptote.  In particular, $f(x)$ approaches 0 as $x$ approaches both $\infty$ and $-\infty.$

Thus, the graph of $y = f(x)$ intersects the graph of $y = x$ exactly once on each of the intervals $(-\infty,1),$ $(1,2),$ $(2,3),$ $\dots,$ $(99,100),$ $(100,\infty).$  Therefore, there are a total of $\boxed{101}$ real solutions.

